## Forge System

This project is managed by the **Forge** autonomous development system. The main Claude Code session acts as the orchestrator, routing work through skills and spawning specialized sub-agents via the Task tool.

- Skills (`/forge`, `/plan`, `/build`, `/sync`, `/ask`) define the orchestration workflow.
- Sub-agents (spawned via Task) handle research, review, testing, and debugging.
- GitHub Issues and PRs are the sole state machine — no local state files.

If you are the main session, run `/forge` to begin. If you were spawned as a sub-agent, follow your task prompt — the rest of this document is shared project context.

### Architecture

```
Main session → /forge (orchestrator skill)
  ├── /sync   — reads GitHub issue/PR state, returns structured summary
  ├── /plan   — spawns 4 research sub-agents in parallel, files GitHub Issues
  ├── /build  — claims one issue, implements, spawns review+test+debug sub-agents, opens PR
  └── /ask    — escalates blocking questions to human via GitHub comments
```

The loop: `/forge` → `/sync` → route to `/plan` or `/build` → back to `/forge` → repeat until all issues are closed or a human decision is needed.

### State Machine

All project state is encoded in GitHub Issue labels:

| Label | Meaning |
|-------|---------|
| `agent:ready` | Dependencies met, available for an agent to claim |
| `agent:in-progress` | An agent is actively working on this issue |
| `agent:done` | PR opened, awaiting human review and merge |
| `agent:blocked` | Waiting on other issues to close first |
| `agent:needs-human` | Blocked on a decision only a human can make |
| `triage` | Human-filed issue, awaiting agent classification on next `/sync` |

`/sync` checks blocked issues and promotes them to ready when their dependencies close. It also classifies `triage` issues, detects stuck `agent:done` issues with no open PR, and reports unlabeled orphan issues.

### Filing Issues

Agent-created issues get labels automatically via `/plan`. For human-filed issues, add the `triage` label — `/sync` will classify it (infer type, set priority) and promote it to `agent:ready`.

### Resumability

There is no local state to lose. If a session ends mid-work:

- GitHub Issues and labels reflect the last known state
- Any in-progress branch has been pushed (or can be abandoned)
- Starting a new `claude` session and running `/forge` picks up exactly where it stopped
- `/sync` detects stale `agent:in-progress` labels and recovers them

### Context Management

After `/plan` completes, use `/clear` before starting the build loop — `/sync` will re-establish all necessary context from GitHub. Do not `/clear` between individual `/build` cycles. Sub-agents spawned via Task have their own context windows and do not consume the main session's.

## Session Start

**At the start of every session, run the `/forge` skill.** This reads the current GitHub state and determines what to do next — plan, build, or surface questions.

## Workflow

- GitHub Issues are the task queue. No issue means no work.
- Every feature is implemented on a feature branch and submitted as a PR.
- PRs require CI to pass (lint + typecheck + test + build) before merge.
- The human approves every PR before it's merged.
- All project state lives in GitHub — nothing important is stored locally.

## Conventions

- Use Server Components by default. Only add `'use client'` when interactivity is needed.
- Fetch data in Server Components, not in client-side effects.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling. No custom CSS files unless absolutely necessary.
- Follow the existing file and component naming patterns.
- Every commit references the issue it closes: `feat: title (closes #N)`
- Co-locate unit tests with source: `Component.tsx` -> `Component.test.tsx`
- E2E tests go in the `e2e/` directory (Playwright, chromium only in CI)

## Do Not

- Write to `.env` files directly — use `vercel env` for environment variables.
- Modify `pnpm-lock.yaml` manually — let `pnpm install` handle it.
- Skip quality checks — always run `pnpm lint && pnpm tsc --noEmit && pnpm test && pnpm build`.
- Work on code without a corresponding GitHub Issue.
- Merge PRs without human approval.
- Modify `CLAUDE.md`, `PROMPT.md`, or files in `.claude/skills/`.

